description:
Hound's Tongue (Cynoglossum grande), also known as Pacific Hound's Tonge ophotographed along the Stevens Creek Nature Trail at Montebello Open Space Preserve in Santa Clara County, CA.  Set contains 2 photos - the lead photo, which provides a close-up of the plant's inflorescence, and a shot showing the entie plant in situ.

When this photograph was taken (early April), this plant was young enough to not have produced any seed-bearing nutlets.  Unfortunately, nutlet characteristics are key to differentiating the genus Cynoglossum from the other genera belonging to the Borage Family.  Even so, the plant's blue-and-white flowers and long, tongue-like leaves are distinctive, so it is hard to to mistake this plant for anything else.

description: Goldback Fern (Pentagramma triangularis), photographed along the Canyon Trail at Montebello Open Space Preserve in Santa Clara County, CA.  This is the well-known fernthat has the cream-to-yellow exudate covering the underside of its leaves, hence its common name.  For this specimen, the exudate is cream-colored, as you can see from the still somewhat-curled-up new leaves.  No other fern in the area has this "dusting" of exudate on the undeside of its leaves, so the exudate is a reliable field mark for P. triangularis.  (There are other ferns that produce an exudate covering the underside of their leaves, but their natural range is well outside the San Francisco Bay Area.)

description:
California Milkmaids (Cardamine californica), photographed along the Stevens Creek Nature Trail at Montebello Open Space Preserve in Santa Clara County, CA.  Identified as such on the basis of the following characteristics (per Jepson's):

1) Four petals, arranged in a "Maltese cross," with 4-6 stamens and a single pistil with a single style  (Gets me to the Mustard Family, Brassicaceae.)
2) Plant generally glabrous (no hairs).
3) Cauline leaves always present; cauline leaves not basally lobed or clasping. (Gets me to Brassicaceae, Group 2).
4) Flowers radial
5) Stamens 6; ovary, young fruit linear.  (See the flower but that is about  to open, as well as the emerging seed capsule to the upper left of the open flower)
6) Cauline leaves compound
7) Plant terrestrial (Gets me to the genus, Cardamine).
8) Cauline leaves pinnately compound, leaflets 3.
9) Sepals 4 mm long, petals 15 mm long.
10) Petals white or pale rose. (Gets me to Cardamine californica.)

Note: C. californica also has rhizomes that produce leaves which are reniform in shape, in contrast to the plant's compount cauline leaves.  I did not see those leaves for this particular specimen (perhaps they were eaten by some animal?), but I did see them on many of the other examples of California Milkmaids that I saw at Montebello.

References:
1) Jepson's e-Flora, "Key to Brassicacea."  Retrieved from http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?key=70 on 4/2/18.
2) Jepson's e-Flora, "Key to Cardamine." Retrieved from http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?key=10483  on 4/2/18.
3) Jepson's e-Flora, "Cardamine californica."  Retrieved from http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/eflora/eflora_display.php?tid=76456 on 4/2/18.

Western Heart's Ease Violet (Viola ocellata), photographed along the Stevens Creek Nature Trail at Montebello Open Space Preserve in Santa Clara County, CA.  Identified as Viola ocellata based on the following (per Jepson's):  

1) Stem present.  (This eliminates 5 species in California that do not have actual stems.)
2) Stipules very much smaller than the leaves; lateral petals very much longer than the sepals.  (This eliminates Viola arvensis.)
3) Leaves simple. (This eliminates four species having compound leaves, including Viola douglasii.)
4) Lower stem prostrate to erect, with leaves and peduncles. (Eliminates V. glabella and all forms of V lobata.)
5) Plat without stolon-like stem. (Eliminates V. sempervirens, which actually has sole-like sems.)
6) Petals white at least adaxially, lateral petals with large purple spots basally, above a small, basal, yellow area.
7) Leaf not shiny; cauline leaf bases cordate to truncate; plant glabrous to puberulent (here, the puberulence is restricted to the leaves and the lower stem). (Eliminates V. cuneata and leaves me with V. ocellata as the logical choice for the species shown in the photograph.)
